<div id="review_61090324" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/61090324" />
    <a title="Kara" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2029512-kara"><img alt="Kara" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/61090324?book_show_action=true">Jun 25, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kara" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kara" href="/user/show/2029512-kara">Kara</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer61090324" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5583707108683369055">This book is a total slog. The Goodreads description calls it meticulous; I call it boring. It kind of lands in gray area between fiction and non-fiction, and it&apos;s pretty obvious that neither Mailer nor Schiller (the principal &quot;researcher&quot;/journalist/producer/opportunist) actually did a face-to-face interview with Gilmore.<br/>As a subject, Gilmore just isn&apos;t that interesting. One of the journalists suggests that Gilmore is &quot;mediocrity enlarged by history,&quot; and that pretty much sums it up. He was a m</span>
  <span id="freeText5583707108683369055" style="display:none">This book is a total slog. The Goodreads description calls it meticulous; I call it boring. It kind of lands in gray area between fiction and non-fiction, and it's pretty obvious that neither Mailer nor Schiller (the principal "researcher"/journalist/producer/opportunist) actually did a face-to-face interview with Gilmore.<br />As a subject, Gilmore just isn't that interesting. One of the journalists suggests that Gilmore is "mediocrity enlarged by history," and that pretty much sums it up. He was a mediocre criminal and an awful human being. Had he ended up with life in prison, rather than a death sentence, no one would written ten words about him.<br />I can't believe this won a Pulitzer.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5583707108683369055" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
